**Version Used**: 3.11.0-4.22108.8 (d9bef045)

**Steps to Reproduce**:
1. Inside Visual Studio, create a new C# `Class Library (.NET Framework)` project.  The type of C# project isn't too important, this is just used for simplicity.
2. Replace the contents of `Class1.cs` with the following code:
```cs
namespace ClassLibrary1
{
    static class Settings
    {
        public static bool IsSpecialMode
        {
            get
            {
                #if SPECIAL_FLAG
                    return true;
                #else
                    return false;
                #endif
            }
        }
    }

    public class Class1
    {
        public string DoSomething()
        {
            if (Settings.IsSpecialMode) {return "Doing something SPECIAL.";}
            else                        {return "Doing something.";}
        }
    }
}
```
4. Build the solution in `Release` mode, then use a developer command prompt to navigate into the output directory and open the built DLL using _ILDASM_.: `ildasm.exe ClassLibrary1.dll`.
5. Navigate down to the `DoSomething()` method and double-click it to bring up the IL.

![image](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/assets/1672416/b2f19d7a-234b-496e-934b-107c3955e9ae)


**Expected Behavior**:
It's my understanding that the `Optimize+` compiler flag removes unreachable code.  Based on whether `SPECIAL_FLAG` is defined, the `Settings.IsSpecialMode` property will always return either `true` or `false`.  As a result of this, there is only a single code path the `DoSomething()` method can ever execute.  It is expected here that the generated IL would reflect this.  Only one string should be seen in the IL.

**Actual Behavior**:
Both strings can be seen in the IL.  Even though one block of the `if` statement in the `DoSomething()` method is unreachable, both blocks are always kept around by the compiler.

**Remarks**
The code above was kept simple for demonstration purposes, but either block of the `if` statement could contain thousands of lines of code.  The compiler should be smart enough to detect this and remove the unreachable code.

Additionally, the idea behind the code above is that a production build should not define `SPECIAL_FLAG`, and all the special code associated with that flag should be compiled out of the final assembly.  Because the unreachable code is not being removed by the compiler, it can still be viewed and coerced into being executed by someone.  The intermediate `IsSpecialMode` property is used to avoid having to clutter the codebase with preprocessor directives.

